Sure. We can start with the basic Docker initialization commands. These are the commands you use when setting up Docker for the first time and starting your container journey.

1. Check Docker installation
docker --version

Example output:

Docker version 28.x.x

Check Docker service:

systemctl status docker
2. Start Docker service

If Docker is not running:

sudo systemctl start docker

Enable Docker after server reboot:

sudo systemctl enable docker
3. Test Docker installation

Run a test container:

docker run hello-world

What happens:

Docker Engine
      |
      Pull image hello-world
      |
      Create container
      |
      Run container
      |
      Stop container
4. Check Docker information
docker info

Shows:

Number of containers
Images
Storage driver
Docker version
5. Check running containers

Only running containers:

docker ps

All containers:

docker ps -a

Example:

CONTAINER ID   IMAGE          STATUS
abc123         nginx          Up 10 minutes
6. Download an image

Example: nginx

docker pull nginx

List downloaded images:

docker images

Output:

REPOSITORY   TAG
nginx        latest
7. Create and run a container

Example:

docker run -d --name mynginx -p 8080:80 nginx

Meaning:

-d          → run in background
--name      → container name
-p          → port mapping
nginx       → image name

Check:

docker ps

Open browser:

http://server-ip:8080
8. Stop and start containers

Stop:

docker stop mynginx

Start again:

docker start mynginx

Restart:

docker restart mynginx
9. Remove container

Stop first:

docker stop mynginx

Remove:

docker rm mynginx
10. Remove image
docker rmi nginx
